authored, male-illustrated works for and about women.In her interdisciplinary investigation of the cultural and political legacy of Anne of Brittany and her female contemporaries, Cynthia J. Brown argues that the verbal and visual imagery used to represent these women of influence was necessarily complex because of its inherently conflicting portrayal of power and subordination. She contends that it can be understood fully only by drawing on the intersection of pertinent literary, historical, codicological, and art historical sources. In The Queen's Library, Brown examines depictions of women of power in five spheres that tellingly expose this tension: rituals of urban and royal reception; the politics of female personification allegories; the "famous-women" topos; women in mourning; and women mourned.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBooks and readingxHistoryv16th century. 0aBooks and readingxHistoryvTo 1500. 0aQueensvBooks and readingvPolitical aspects. 0aQueensxBooks and readingxPolitical aspects. 0aWomen and literaturevPolitical aspects. 0aWomen and literaturexPolitical aspects. 0aWomenvBooks and readingvPolitical aspects. 0aWomenxBooks and readingxPolitical aspects. 0aWomenxHistoryvMiddle Ages, 500-1500. 0aWomenxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 500-1500. 4aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aGender Studies.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9780812204